longDescription: bird's-eye view of South Avenue, looking south from Main Street. The view shows the Genesee River to the right, the Erie Canal Aqueduct, and the Court Street Bridge. South Avenue was first known as River Street. It was renamed South St. Paul Street in 1838. In 1899, the length of street from Main Street to the city line was named South Avenue.

title: Aquaduct Inner Divider Wall
shortDescription: Albert R. Stone Negative Collection; inner divider wall of the aqueduct; a ladder and a pile of slats/bricks lays against it
longDescription:
The Iconic Aqueduct
When built, the Rochester aqueduct was declared the longest stone bridge in America; it survived the annual floods of the Genesee River.  After the canal was diverted south to cross the Genesee River at Genesee Valley Park, the aqueduct became the Broad Street Bridge for autos and pedestrians.

The sun streams through the open arches of the Aqueduct over the Genesee River, creating rectangular patches of light on the Aqueduct floor.  Construction debris sits along the raised curb under the center set of arches.  These center arches divide  the new "subway street" bridge into two lanes, allowing the Interurban trains to run where Erie Canal boats once did.  A short ladder rests against the bottom of one arch, allowing workers to cross into the other lane.

negative, glass plate
overall: 5 x 7 in.
tags: aqueduct, construction, black and white image, history
citation: Stone, Albert R. Aqueduct’s Arches Look like Medieval Cloister. n.d. New York Heritage Digital Collections. https://nyheritage.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/p15109coll11/id/288/rec/10.

title: Side view of Broad Street Bridge with cables
shortDescription: View of aqueduct's side
longDescription: Cables lead to the side of the Broad Street Bridge, indicating that this photograph was taken during the reconstruction that transformed the Aqueduct into Broad Street and a "subway bridge". Pipes are attached between the arches on the lower level and a parapet lines the cantilevered pedestrian walkway on the upper level. Osburn House is visible at the end of the bridge. The waters of the Genesee River swirl around the base of the bridge.
publisher: Albert R. Stone Negative Collection, Rochester Museum & Science Center
citation: Stone, Albert R. Side View of Broad Street Bridge with Cables. 1924. Photograph. Albert R. Stone Negative Collection, Rochester Museum & Science Center, January 1, 1924.

title: Aqueduct with subway tracks
shortDescription: Tracks go through the aqueduct
longDescription: A view of the Broad Street bridge facing northwest, showing a stairway leading to the subway beneath the bridge. The concrete structure in the lower left is a bridge over a spillway connecting the old Rochester, Fitzhugh and Carroll Mill Race with the Genesee River. The upper left background shows from left to right, City Hall and the Times Square Building.
publisher: Albert R. Stone Negative Collection, Rochester Museum & Science Center
citation: Stone, Albert R. Aqueduct with Subway Tracks. 1929. Photograph. Albert R. Stone Negative Collection, Rochester Museum & Science Center, 1929.
